Buckinghamshire, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Church, Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheddington, Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England":"Cheddington, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheddington, Buckinghamshire, England":"Cheddington, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Treadway","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>treden</i> ‘to tread, trample’ + <i>wei(e)</i> ‘way’, perhaps used for a vagrant or a well-traveled man."],"variants":[{"name":"Tredway","meanings":["English: variant of   Treadway  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Treadaway","meanings":["English: variant of   Treadway  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Devon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly North American: of uncertain origin. It is found among Jews as well as gentiles. Among the latter it is generally from the name of the English county, either directly or as a transferred use of the surname, which derives from a British tribal name said to mean ‘worshippers of the god Dumnōnos’."],"variants":[{"name":"Devonne","meanings":["Mainly North American: of uncertain origin. It is found among Jews as well as gentiles. Among the latter it is generally from the name of the English county, either directly or as a transferred use of the surname, which derives from a British tribal name said to mean ‘worshippers of the god Dumnōnos’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":58,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":85,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":87,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Devon Treadway was born in 1500, in Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England as the son of Edmond Treadway. He married Margaret Chapman before 1523, in Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1594, in Cheddington, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 94."},"et":{"1500–1594":"1500–1594","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1532–1558":"1532–1558","1534–Male":"1534–Surnud","1483–1522":"1483–1522","before 1523":"enne 1523","1558":"1558","1534":"1534","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","1532":"1532","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1550":"1550","1594":"1594","1483":"1483","1549":"1549","Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Church, Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheddington, Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England":"Cheddington, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheddington, Buckinghamshire, England":"Cheddington, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1500–1594":"1500–1594","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1532–1558":"1532–1558","1534–Male":"1534–Kuollut","1483–1522":"1483–1522","before 1523":"ennen vuotta 1523","1558":"1558","1534":"1534","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","1532":"1532","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1550":"1550","1594":"1594","1483":"1483","1549":"1549","Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Church, Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Y